<topic id="topic_hcd_hh5_qdc">
  <title>Webinar WN 27</title>
  <body>
    <p><i>"Improved review and editing capabilities, support for Markdown and other non-XML files in
        the file comparison and merge tool, and experimental support for editing DITA maps in a
        specialized tree editor for the benefit of Oxygen XML Web Author users."</i></p>
    <p>The features added in version 27 of Web Author allows you to do more in less time. There are
      many features but I'll mention just a few. You can see all of them in the What's New page on
      oxygenxml.com.</p>
    <p>This version brings new capabilities to edit/manipulate documents with AI Positron and
      features that allows to see, inspect, refine proposed AI changes with ease/confidence. Now you
      can inspect each piece of text proposed by AI with the diff on text mode, so you can visualize
      differences up to the individual plain text characters BEFORE accepting the change in your
      document.</p>
    <p>Beside that you can now add color highlights to the document. So you can mark a specific part
      of the document with a color so that a co-reviewers knows what requires special attention. You
      can choose from a palette o colors.</p>
    <p>And last but not least the specialized DITA map editor allows you to visualize and edit a
      DITA map as natural as possible, focused on the tree structure. This blends well with the
      Intelligent Agent actions (Split Topic, Expand Draft) that can topics to the DITA Map, because
      this specialized tree-editor allows you to, for example, move the slitted topic to a proper
      location in the map.</p>
    <p>Let's see each feature in action.</p>
    <section id="section_cx3_kh5_qdc">
      <title>Improved review and editing capabilities</title>
      <p>The review and editing capabilities are uplifted in version 27 by a few features:<ul
          id="ul_o5f_4k5_qdc">
          <li>Color Highlights</li>
          <li>Outline available on concurrent editing</li>
          <li>AI</li>
        </ul></p>
      <p>You can add color highlights by choosing a color then simply selecting zones in the
        document, just as natural you would do with a highlighter on a paper. You can all
        highlighted texts in the Review side-panel, you don't have to scroll and look for highlights
        in the document.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="section_d4q_kh5_qdc">
      <title>Diff and merge Markdown and plain text files </title>
      <p>Prior to version 27 the Web Author had a diff and merge tool that allows to see and merge
        differences between XML documents and the differences were presented in author-mode, not on
        XML source.</p>
      <p>The version 27 brings:</p>
      <ul id="ul_wjc_zk5_qdc">
        <li>Diff and Merge on Markdown and text-plain files.</li>
        <li>Toggle Text Mode diff on XML documents</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The diff and merge support can be used directly within the application with the compare
        actions, it allows resolving conflicts when committing on Git, previewing AI Positron
        proposed changes, etc. But it can be also used to build diff links in your workflow. For
        example we have a Git Hook that intercepts commits in our manual and builds diff links and
        comment them on Jira to facilitate documentation review process.</p>
      <p>The diff on text mode allows full transparency when accepting AI changes.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="section_ikh_nh5_qdc">
      <title>Experimental support for editing DITA maps in a specialized tree editor</title>
      <p>Web Author 27 comes with a supports for a specialized DITA Map editor, inspired from the
        so-loved DITA Maps Manager from Oxygen XML Editor. In the long run we aim to offer a similar
        editing experience with DITA Maps Manager in Oxygen XML Web Author. This release allows
        integrators to activate/integrate the specialized tree-editor for DITA Map files instead of
        the author editor. In the following releases we plan to have the DITA Map side-view
        editable, at least for the Git connector, so if you have any feedback, ideas about the
        integration feel free to ask.</p>
      <p>The DITA Map specialized editor presents the document as a tree and allows you to drag and
        drop nodes, promote/demote, etc. Compared to the author mode, the tree-mode allows you to
        focus on the hierarchy of topics more, eliminating unnecessary complexity like tags. It
        shows the tree just as presented in TOC, it shows by default titles instead of hrefs.</p>
      <p>Integrators can enable this feature by specifying an URL parameter after verifying that
        it's compatible with their connector. I won't get you through the specific details of the
        integration, for that you can contact on support@oxygenxml.com. I'll show you how the DITA
        Map tree mode was successfully integrated in Oxygen Content Fusion, with the mention that
        Oxygen Content Fusion includes the same editing core/module (that's available in) as Web
        Author.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="section_c53_zvc_rdc">
      <title>AI</title>
      <p>The greatest increment that the latest version adds regarding AI is that now you have
        Intelligent Agents actions that don't just walk text from your document to OpenAI and back,
        now Positron can do boring tasks for you like splitting a topic in multiple topics and
        insert them to the map. Latest Positron enables/allows AI to access DITA Map, you can use
        the chat to add a new topic in the map.</p>
